 on retirement savings, the cost and efficiency of medical resources, and the predictors of health events. The volume begins with a discussion of the risks and merits of 401(k) plans. Subsequent chapters present recent analysis of the growth of Medicare costs; the different aspects of disability; and the evolution of health, wealth, and living arrangements over the life course. Keeping with the global tradition of previous volumes, Analyses in the Economics of Aging also includes comparative studies on savings behavior in Italy, the Netherlands, and the United States; an examination of household savings among different age groups in Germany; and a chapter devoted to population aging and the plight of widows in India. Carefully compiled and containing some of the most cutting-edge research and analysis available, this volume should be of interest to any specialist or policymaker concerned with ongoing changes in savings and retirement behaviors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAging. 0aMedicare. 0aOlder people. 0aRetirement income. 0aSocial sciences. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aeconomics, economical, aging, age, political economy, retirement savings, retire, old, elderly, older, medical resources, health events, healthy, healthcare, 401 k plans, medicare costs, disability, disabilities, wealth, money, finances, living arrangements, comparative studies, italy, italian, netherlands, united states of america, usa, american, households, germany, german, population, populous, india, indian, policymaker, risk, technology, institutions, survival curves.1 aBörsch-Supan, Axel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCase, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, James J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct